HEADWORD: Trental
<hw>Tren"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>trentale</ets>, fr. L. <ets>triginta</ets> thirty; akin to
<ets>tres</ets> three: cf. OF. <ets>trentel</ets>. See <er>Three</er>,
and cf. <er>Trigintal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>
<def>An office and mass for the dead on the thirtieth day after death or
burial.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Their <xex>trentals</xex> and their shrifts.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a dirge; an elegy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trente et quarante</ent>⟦br⟧
